From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ci <ci@local>
Date: Fri, 23 May 2026 22:30:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fsl/dpaa: add NO_TXCONFIRM offload TX FQ allocator

PR14z23 — silicon-level suppression of per-frame TX-confirmation work
on the FMan PCD HIT path.

Background.  PR14z22 step-1 (diagnostic patch 0053, since reverted)
disambiguated the M2 acceptance-gate softirq wedge: with the cc_v4_tcp
miss-action set to DROP, iperf3 still ran at 6.945 Gbps, proving the
silicon CC HIT path was functionally correct and frames were going
eth3 RX -> eth4 TX without traversing the kernel RX NAPI poller.  The
remaining 15.97% softirq floor (and the M2 5%-CPU gate failure) is the
**TX-confirmation NAPI poll** — dpaa_eth_napi_poll() processing the
per-CPU TX-confirm FQ that silicon enqueues a Frame Descriptor onto
for every transmitted frame.  At ~1.6 Mpps egress across 4 CPUs the
per-frame skb-free cost is ~50 ns -> ~16% per-CPU floor.

Architectural conclusion (see plans/PR14z23-DESIGN.md "Options A and
B EXECUTED, BOTH RULED OUT"): sysctl netdev_budget tuning (Option A)
produces +5pts regression; threaded NAPI (Option B) produces +40pts
regression because DPAA1 QMan portals are strictly per-CPU silicon
and Linux-side knobs cannot redistribute the per-frame TX-confirm
cost.  Only Option C — suppression of the TX-confirm FD enqueue at
the silicon level — can reach the gate.

The legacy ASK 1.x sdk_dpaa fork solved this by allocating dedicated
no-confirm TX FQs (QM_INITFQ_WE_CONTEXTA with B0V=0) for
silicon-offloaded HIT-path traffic and routing CC-HIT enqueues
through them; that is how it reached >9 Gbps line rate at <5% CPU.
The legacy reference is tmp-mono-ask/cdx/devman.c lines 290-330,
which used context_a.hi=0x9a000000 lo=0xC0000000 (OVFQ|A2V|A0V|EBD,
B0V=0).  Mainline dpaa_eth.c at the existing FQ_TYPE_TX path uses
0x1e00000080000000ULL (OVOM|A2V|A0V|B0V|EBD); clearing B0V (bit 1
of the high byte) gives 0x1c00000080000000ULL — identical to the
mainline pattern except for the suppressed confirmation enqueue.
EBD is preserved so FMan still recycles the BMan buffer after TX
(RISK#1 in PR14z23-DESIGN.md).

This patch adds:

  1. A new enum value FQ_TYPE_TX_NO_CONFIRM in dpaa_eth.h.

  2. dpaa_alloc_offload_tx_fq(struct net_device *dev, u32 *fqid),
     exported via <linux/fsl/dpaa_flow_offload.h>, that allocates a
     fresh dynamic-FQID dpaa_fq of the new type, inherits the
     existing TX QMan channel from priv->egress_fqs[0]->channel
     (the FMan TX port's channel as resolved by
     fman_port_get_qman_channel_id() at probe), assigns WQ 6 (same
     as best-effort FQ_TYPE_TX), splices it into priv->dpaa_fq_list
     so retire/cleanup runs at port removal, and runs the standard
     dpaa_fq_init() path.

  3. A switch-case treatment in dpaa_fq_init() for the new type
     that mirrors the FQ_TYPE_TX path (CGR membership, OAL/OAC) but
     programs context_a directly with 0x1c00000080000000ULL,
     suppressing the silicon TX-confirm enqueue.

The consumer (ask_hw.c) is updated in patch 0054.

No regression risk for non-offloaded traffic.  Existing FQ_TYPE_TX,
FQ_TYPE_TX_CONFIRM, FQ_TYPE_TX_CONF_MQ paths are unchanged.  Kernel
control-plane (dpaa_xmit), ARP, and the conntrack-promote chain
continue to use the existing TX FQs with confirmation enabled.

Signed-off-by: ASK2 build bot <ask2-build@kralj.dev>
---
 .../net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.c    | 80 ++++++++++++++++++-
 .../net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h    |  1 +
 include/linux/fsl/dpaa_flow_offload.h         | 37 ++++++++-
 3 files changed, 116 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.c
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.c
@@ -528,6 +528,76 @@ int dpaa_get_fman_port_id(struct net_device *dev, u8 *port_id)
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(dpaa_get_fman_port_id);
 
+/**
+ * dpaa_alloc_offload_tx_fq() - allocate a TX FQ with TX confirmation
+ * suppressed at the silicon level.
+ *
+ * See <linux/fsl/dpaa_flow_offload.h> for the full contract.  PR14z23.
+ *
+ * Allocates a fresh dynamic-FQID dpaa_fq tagged FQ_TYPE_TX_NO_CONFIRM,
+ * inherits the FMan TX port's QMan channel from the existing
+ * priv->egress_fqs[0] (which was set by dpaa_setup_egress() at probe
+ * via fman_port_get_qman_channel_id()), assigns WQ 6 (same as the
+ * best-effort FQ_TYPE_TX class), splices it into priv->dpaa_fq_list
+ * so retire/cleanup runs at port-remove time, and runs the standard
+ * dpaa_fq_init() path — which for FQ_TYPE_TX_NO_CONFIRM programs
+ * context_a = 0x1c00000080000000ULL (B0V=0, no confirm-FQ enqueue).
+ *
+ * Used by the ASK2 FMan PCD HIT path (ask_hw.c) as the sink for
+ * silicon-offloaded forwarded flows.  When the CC node's per-key
+ * FORWARD_FQ action points at this FQID instead of the kernel's
+ * default egress_fqs[0], FMan still transmits the frame on the wire
+ * but does NOT enqueue a TX-confirmation FD to the per-CPU TX-confirm
+ * FQ — eliminating the dpaa_eth_napi_poll() per-frame work that
+ * pinned NET_KERNEL_CPU at the ~16% floor in the PR14z22 step-1
+ * measurement.
+ */
+int dpaa_alloc_offload_tx_fq(struct net_device *dev, u32 *fqid)
+{
+	struct dpaa_priv *priv;
+	struct dpaa_fq *dpaa_fq;
+	struct device *parent;
+	u16 tx_channel;
+	int err;
+
+	if (!dev || !fqid)
+		return -EINVAL;
+
+	if (dev->netdev_ops != &dpaa_ops)
+		return -ENODEV;
+
+	priv = netdev_priv(dev);
+	parent = dev->dev.parent;
+
+	/* The FMan TX port's QMan channel is resolved at probe by
+	 * dpaa_setup_egress() and stored on each TX FQ.  Inherit from
+	 * egress_fqs[0] — guaranteed populated by probe before any
+	 * external module can resolve the netdev. */
+	if (!priv->egress_fqs || !priv->egress_fqs[0])
+		return -ENOENT;
+	tx_channel = priv->egress_fqs[0]->channel;
+
+	dpaa_fq = devm_kzalloc(parent, sizeof(*dpaa_fq), GFP_KERNEL);
+	if (!dpaa_fq)
+		return -ENOMEM;
+
+	dpaa_fq->fq_type = FQ_TYPE_TX_NO_CONFIRM;
+	dpaa_fq->net_dev = dev;
+	dpaa_fq->channel = tx_channel;
+	dpaa_fq->wq = 6;		/* match best-effort FQ_TYPE_TX */
+	dpaa_fq->fqid = 0;		/* dynamic */
+	dpaa_fq->flags = QMAN_FQ_FLAG_TO_DCPORTAL;
+	INIT_LIST_HEAD(&dpaa_fq->list);
+	list_add_tail(&dpaa_fq->list, &priv->dpaa_fq_list);
+
+	err = dpaa_fq_init(dpaa_fq, false);
+	if (err) {
+		list_del(&dpaa_fq->list);
+		return err;
+	}
+
+	*fqid = dpaa_fq->fqid;
+	return 0;
+}
+EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(dpaa_alloc_offload_tx_fq);
+
 static int dpaa_setup_tc(struct net_device *net_dev, enum tc_setup_type type,
  void *type_data)
 {
@@ -1359,7 +1429,8 @@ static int dpaa_fq_init(struct dpaa_fq *dpaa_fq, bool td_enable)
 		 * place them in the netdev's CGR, along with the Tx FQs.
 		 */
 		if (dpaa_fq->fq_type == FQ_TYPE_TX ||
 		    dpaa_fq->fq_type == FQ_TYPE_TX_CONFIRM ||
-		    dpaa_fq->fq_type == FQ_TYPE_TX_CONF_MQ) {
+		    dpaa_fq->fq_type == FQ_TYPE_TX_CONF_MQ ||
+		    dpaa_fq->fq_type == FQ_TYPE_TX_NO_CONFIRM) {
 			initfq.we_mask |= cpu_to_be16(QM_INITFQ_WE_CGID);
 			initfq.fqd.fq_ctrl |= cpu_to_be16(QM_FQCTRL_CGE);
 			initfq.fqd.cgid = (u8)priv->cgr_data.cgr.cgrid;
@@ -1405,6 +1476,13 @@ static int dpaa_fq_init(struct dpaa_fq *dpaa_fq, bool td_enable)
 			}
 		}
 
+		/* PR14z23: silicon-suppressed TX confirmation.  Same
+		 * context_a layout as FQ_TYPE_TX (OVOM|A2V|A0V|EBD) but
+		 * B0V=0 so FMan does NOT enqueue a TX-confirm FD on
+		 * each transmit.  No conf_fqs[] lookup. */
+		if (dpaa_fq->fq_type == FQ_TYPE_TX_NO_CONFIRM) {
+			initfq.we_mask |= cpu_to_be16(QM_INITFQ_WE_CONTEXTA);
+			qm_fqd_context_a_set64(&initfq.fqd,
+					       0x1c00000080000000ULL);
+		}
+
 		/* Put all the ingress queues in our "ingress CGR". */
 		if (priv->use_ingress_cgr &&
 		    (dpaa_fq->fq_type == FQ_TYPE_RX_DEFAULT ||
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h
@@ -27,6 +27,7 @@ enum dpaa_fq_type {
 	FQ_TYPE_TX_CONFIRM,	/* Tx default Conf FQ (actually an Rx FQ) */
 	FQ_TYPE_TX_CONF_MQ,	/* Tx conf FQs (one for each Tx FQ) */
 	FQ_TYPE_TX_ERROR,	/* Tx Error FQs (these are actually Rx FQs) */
+	FQ_TYPE_TX_NO_CONFIRM,	/* PR14z23: HW-offload TX FQ (no confirm) */
 };
 
 struct dpaa_fq {
diff --git a/include/linux/fsl/dpaa_flow_offload.h b/include/linux/fsl/dpaa_flow_offload.h
--- a/include/linux/fsl/dpaa_flow_offload.h
+++ b/include/linux/fsl/dpaa_flow_offload.h
@@ -122,6 +122,38 @@ int dpaa_get_fman_port_id(struct net_device *dev, u8 *port_id);
  * [0, dpaa_max_num_txqs()) is populated at probe time).
  */
 int dpaa_get_tx_fqid(struct net_device *dev, u32 queue, u32 *fqid);
+
+/**
+ * dpaa_alloc_offload_tx_fq() - allocate a TX FQ with TX confirmation
+ * suppressed at the silicon level.
+ * @dev:   a netdev that may or may not be backed by the dpaa Ethernet
+ *         driver (caller is allowed to pass any net_device — the
+ *         helper returns -ENODEV if @dev is not a dpaa port).
+ * @fqid:  out-param; on success receives the FQID of the newly
+ *         allocated no-confirm TX FQ.
+ *
+ * Allocates a fresh dynamic-FQID dpaa_fq tagged FQ_TYPE_TX_NO_CONFIRM
+ * and initialises it with context_a programmed to suppress the silicon
+ * TX-confirm FD enqueue (B0V=0).  The FQ inherits the FMan TX port's
+ * QMan channel from the netdev's existing TX FQs and assigns WQ 6
+ * (best-effort).  The new FQ is appended to priv->dpaa_fq_list so its
+ * retire/cleanup runs at port-remove time alongside the regular TX
+ * FQs.
+ *
+ * Intended for the ASK2 FMan PCD HIT path: a CC-node FORWARD_FQ
+ * action pointed at @fqid will silicon-transmit the matched frame
+ * without queueing a TX-confirmation FD onto the per-CPU TX-confirm
+ * FQ.  This eliminates the dpaa_eth_napi_poll() per-frame work that
+ * accounts for the ~16% NET_KERNEL_CPU floor on the M2 acceptance
+ * gate (PR14z22 step-1 measurement).
+ *
+ * Each call allocates a NEW FQ — callers wanting per-port singletons
+ * (typical) must cache the returned FQID themselves.
+ *
+ * Return: 0 on success with *fqid populated, -EINVAL on NULL args,
+ * -ENODEV if @dev is not a dpaa-backed netdev, -ENOENT if the netdev's
+ * egress_fqs[] is not yet populated (probe-ordering bug), -ENOMEM on
+ * allocation failure.
+ */
+int dpaa_alloc_offload_tx_fq(struct net_device *dev, u32 *fqid);
 #else
 static inline int
 dpaa_register_flow_offload_handler(const struct dpaa_flow_offload_ops *ops)
@@ -150,6 +182,11 @@ dpaa_get_tx_fqid(struct net_device *dev, u32 queue, u32 *fqid)
 {
 	return -ENODEV;
 }
+static inline int
+dpaa_alloc_offload_tx_fq(struct net_device *dev, u32 *fqid)
+{
+	return -ENODEV;
+}
 #endif
 
 #endif /* _LINUX_FSL_DPAA_FLOW_OFFLOAD_H */
